================================================================
PRACTICAL NO. 6 - EXCEL AUTOMATION IN UIPATH
================================================================

PRE-REQUISITES:
- UiPath Studio installed (Community Edition is free)
- Microsoft Excel installed
- UiPath.Excel.Activities package installed
  (In Studio → Manage Packages → search "Excel" → Install)

================================================================
PRACTICAL 6(a) - Automate Read, Write and Append Operations on an Excel File
================================================================

DIFFICULTY: Easy-Medium

WHAT YOU WILL DO:
You will create a UiPath workflow that:
1. READS data from an existing Excel file
2. WRITES new data into the Excel file
3. APPENDS additional data at the end of existing data

--- STEP-BY-STEP INSTRUCTIONS ---

PART 1 - SETUP

Step 1: Create a sample Excel file first.
  - Open Microsoft Excel
  - In Sheet1, type the following in cells A1 to A5:
      A1: Name
      A2: Alice
      A3: Bob
      A4: Charlie
      A5: Diana
  - Save the file as "students.xlsx" on your Desktop

Step 2: Open UiPath Studio.
  - Click "New Project" → Select "Process"
  - Name it: Practical_6a_ExcelOperations
  - Click Create

Step 3: Make sure the Excel Activities package is installed.
  - Go to Manage Packages (top ribbon)
  - Search for "UiPath.Excel.Activities"
  - If not installed, click Install → Save

PART 2 - READ OPERATION

Step 4: In the Designer panel, drag an "Excel Application Scope" activity 
        into the Main sequence.
  - In the "WorkbookPath" field, click the folder icon and browse to 
    your "students.xlsx" file on the Desktop.
    OR type the full path in quotes: "C:\Users\YourName\Desktop\students.xlsx"

Step 5: Inside the Excel Application Scope, drag a "Read Range" activity.
  - Set SheetName to: "Sheet1"
  - Set Range to: "" (empty string means read all data)
  - In the Output section, click the DataTable field → click Ctrl+K 
    to create a new variable → name it: dtStudents

Step 6: After the Excel Application Scope, drag a "Message Box" activity.
  - In the Text field type: dtStudents.Rows.Count.ToString + " rows read from Excel"
  - This will show how many rows were read.

Step 7: Run the workflow (F5 or press Run button).
  - A message box should appear saying "5 rows read from Excel"
  - This confirms the READ operation is working.

PART 3 - WRITE OPERATION

Step 8: Go back inside the Excel Application Scope.
  - After the Read Range activity, drag a "Write Cell" activity.
  - Set SheetName: "Sheet1"
  - Set Cell: "B1"
  - Set Value: "Grade"
  - This writes the header "Grade" into cell B1.

Step 9: Drag another "Write Cell" activity below the previous one.
  - Cell: "B2"  → Value: "A"
  Drag another:
  - Cell: "B3"  → Value: "B"
  Drag another:
  - Cell: "B4"  → Value: "A+"
  Drag another:
  - Cell: "B5"  → Value: "B+"

Step 10: Run the workflow (F5).
  - Open "students.xlsx" — you should see the Grade column filled in.

PART 4 - APPEND OPERATION

Step 11: Create a DataTable to append.
  - Before the Excel Application Scope, drag a "Build Data Table" activity.
  - Click "DataTable" button to open the builder.
  - Add Column: Name it "Name" (String type)
  - Add a row: type "Eve" under Name
  - Click OK
  - In Output → DataTable field, press Ctrl+K → name it: dtNewRow

Step 12: Inside the Excel Application Scope, after the Write Cell activities,
         drag an "Append Range" activity.
  - SheetName: "Sheet1"
  - DataTable: dtNewRow
  - This will add "Eve" at the end of the existing list.

Step 13: Run the workflow (F5).
  - Open "students.xlsx" — you should see "Eve" added in row 6.

EXPECTED FINAL OUTPUT:
  Column A        Column B
  Name            Grade
  Alice           A
  Bob             B
  Charlie         A+
  Diana           B+
  Eve             (blank — just appended name)



================================================================
EXTRA NOTES FOR PRACTICAL 6:
================================================================
- "Excel Application Scope" is the container for all Excel activities.
  Always put your Read/Write activities INSIDE it.
- "Read Range" reads into a DataTable (like a table in memory).
- "Write Range" writes a full DataTable back to Excel.
- "Append Range" adds rows at the bottom of existing data.
- "Write Cell" writes one specific cell at a time.
- Always save Excel file BEFORE running UiPath if you want fresh data.
- If you get an error about Excel being open, close the Excel file first.
